It's not just slice of life. It's those moments where you are safe, at ease, and have the small comforts of the moment. As >>20735863 it's meaning shifts from person to person. And it isn't always about the comfort of someone holding you or holding someone else. I'd say it is about engaging the senses.

>Rain on a hot summer day while you sit under the cover of a porch and enjoy the moment.
>The warmth of your covers chasing away the chill of early morning.
>How your favorite seat conforms to your body after a long day of work.
>The soothing patter of a shower against your skin.

Now obviously in the fiction you'll find here those sensations involve another person. But it's worth pointing out that isn't the rule.

The first thing I think of is a contrast between a happy little scene and something else that is going on elsewhere that is unpleasant. Having something bad be acknowledged highlights how nice and cozy things are now. The easiest example is bad weather outside of a building vs a well built house stocked with everything one could need (in the case of this thread, that would include some loving and very hugable creature). The contrast could also be the POV character's job vs their love life, or their childhood vs their current life, or the demons of a traumatic experience vs the last person keeping them sane.
Just my first thought. The blankets and hot coco are optional.

I have trouble even reading my own work, despite receiving good remarks and advice). You just have to overcome that feeling and bite the bullet, though; a good chef MUST taste his/her own food. Ask people you can trust (preferably fellow writers) to proofread your work, make it clear that you want sharp, fine-pointed critique. If you love the story you want to share with readers, it's worth the effort, even if it doesn't quite feel like it's worth it.

>>20752896
Reading my own work is the second most difficult thing I can do (it falls after starting). Don't let it get you down. The majority of the work you will ever do when writing is revising. Revise, revise, revise. Get some critique, then implement some revisions based on the counsel you've received. The problem with craft hobbies is that there's only one real way to git gud. Don't let it intimidate you, you can only fail by giving up.

When I feel that way, I like to ask for opinions. You can rewrite your story over any length of time, but to gauge how effective any alteration or retcon might be, you should run it by someone. However, consider that after writing something, you're intrinsically creating NEW ideas that improve upon the original material. That's growth; the start-to-finish process of writing your story and the profound satisfaction you feel after completing it is better enabling you to make plot threads and connections you didn't before. You'll conjure up theories and ideas that will improve upon your work, but honestly, you';re probably better off moving on to something new. Rewrites aside (which are essentially new stories), it's not that your original story is lacking in any way, you're just ready to begin implementing your NEW ideas into your NEW stories. You're a creative, you deserve to create something new as opposed to dwelling on something already created and working well on its own in the sense that your audience generally appreciates it as is.
